# SclJet range index-seek

`WHERE <indexed col> op K` for `>`, `>=`, `<`, `<=`, and `BETWEEN lo AND hi` now uses the index: the
descent (and its ordered-walk fallback) is generalized from an equality key to an `IndexRange`,
pruning to the subtrees whose divider range overlaps the query range and collecting the rowids whose
key is in range. The collected rowids are sorted into rowid order so the result is byte-identical to
the full scan. Every result matches reference sqlite3 (verified out-of-band); locked across
`[int, js]`.

[ByteSlice, SqliteValue, SqlInteger, buildTableDatabase](std/scljet/index.ssc)
[queryImage, executeMutation, renderRows](std/scljet/sql.ssc)

```scalascript
def apply(db: ByteSlice, sql: String): ByteSlice =
  executeMutation(db, sql) match
    case Left(m) =>
      println(sql + " => ERR:" + m)
      db
    case Right(next) => next

def show(db: ByteSlice, sql: String): Unit =
  queryImage(db, sql) match
    case Left(m) => println(sql + " => ERR:" + m)
    case Right(rows) => println(sql + " => " + renderRows(rows).toString)

buildTableDatabase(512, 1, 1, "t", "CREATE TABLE t(id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, k INTEGER)",
  List(List(SqlInteger(99L), SqlInteger(0L)))) match
  case Left(error) => println("build-error:" + error.message)
  case Right(db0) =>
    val d1 = apply(db0, "DELETE FROM t")
    val d2 = apply(d1, "CREATE INDEX idx_k ON t(k)")
    val db = apply(d2, "INSERT INTO t VALUES (1,10),(2,20),(3,30),(4,40),(5,50),(6,25),(7,35)")
    show(db, "SELECT id FROM t WHERE k > 30 ORDER BY id")
    show(db, "SELECT id FROM t WHERE k >= 30 ORDER BY id")
    show(db, "SELECT id FROM t WHERE k < 25 ORDER BY id")
    show(db, "SELECT id FROM t WHERE k <= 25 ORDER BY id")
    show(db, "SELECT id FROM t WHERE k BETWEEN 20 AND 35 ORDER BY id")
    show(db, "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM t WHERE k > 100")
    show(db, "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM t WHERE k >= 10")
```
